file-name: XC513593-Green-backed Flycatcher-calls-4-Xeno-Kledang-Sayong Forest Reserve, Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia-27th December 2019.mp3
rmk: Observed a male Green-backed Flycatcher (Narcissus Flycatcher Ficedula narcissina elisae) feeding on the fruit of the Macaranga bancana. It was intermittently making the sharp “tek tek” calls with a posture suggesting ‘defence’ with the body arched, tail lifted and of under-tail coverts flashed. All this suggest maintenance or protection of winter feeding territories.
A series of alarm calls from a migrant. Cause of alarm unknown but not thought to be recordist.

rmk: Female was calling low in the bush. The song was soft  and barely audible
Song was quite soft in real life and is amplified. High frequency calls (bulbul like song) from the flycatcher. Constant descending calls are from Moustached Babblers.

The recording was edited to remove some background jungle sounds (especially loud hum of insects) and amplified. The adult male bird was seen in primary jungle on a hill slope and was foraging in trees at 4-5 meters height. This particular song was heard often and for long periods. The songs I heard today were long and rambling, going up and down in intensity – like a warble. In general they were not easy to hear against the background of loud insect hum of the jungle. The bird would lift the head and beak up, the throat would get full. Occasionally, during calls, the beak did not open.

The recording was edited to remove loud background jungle sounds (especially loud hum of insects) and amplified. The adult male bird was seen in primary jungle on a hill slope and was foraging in trees at 4-5 meters height. This particular call was heard less only at one stretch. Most of the time the bird was heard in song. Rode VideoMic Pro Plus Shotgun Microphone used.

file-name: XC114402-Ficedula_elisae-FL (cf imm) male song Panti Forest, Johor 3Dec12 LS113133.mp3
rmk:
I had brief views of this bird: it had distinctive yellowish underparts with the exception of white undertail coverts, a yellow rump, fairly plain looking head and narrow slighly off-white double wing bars. I could not ascertain the exact colour of the upperparts. Based on the scratchy song and the colour of the underparts, this bird was identified as F. elisae. Since it had a yellow rump I assume it was a male, but probably not a full adult.

The bird was singing in the sub-canopy of an 8m-tall tree at the forest edge.
